    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-11-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="421"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d421">
                <head>421. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3" type="from"
                        >Rusk</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="to"
                        >Kennedy</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d421fn0">Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                            >Kennedy</persName> Library, National Security Files, Countries Series,
                        South Africa. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-11-06">November 6, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Security Council Meeting on South Africa</item>
                </list>
                <p>Enclosed is a paper<note n="1" xml:id="d421fn1">Attached to the source text, but
                        not printed.</note> which describes the approach we plan to take in the
                    forthcoming Security Council meeting on the problem of apartheid in South
                    Africa. This policy has been developed in close consultation with Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">Stevenson</persName>.</p>
                <p>We propose to continue opposing mandatory sanctions and to indicate clearly the
                    limits of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> measures which we think appropriate
                    to deal with the problem. At the same time, in order to show our continuing
                    concern about apartheid and to help deflect support from a more radical
                    resolution, we would be prepared to interpret our existing policy on arms
                    restrictions to include an embargo on materials used primarily in the production
                    of arms and ammunition. The Norwegians have developed such a proposition;
                    Governor <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">Stevenson</persName> will be working with
                    them and other Council members to obtain a resolution satisfactory to us. In
                    addition, we would be prepared to accept a suitable version of an expert
                    committee to study the South African problem.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dean Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
